The paper deals with sequential decision making in partially observable environments shared with other agents, which is a problem commonly studied in the fields of artificial intelligence (cs.AI), game theory (cs.GT), and multi-agent systems (cs.MA). The paper also presents methods for reducing the computational complexity of solving interactive dynamic influence diagrams, which involves graphical models and probabilistic reasoning, making it relevant to the sub-fields of machine learning (cs.LG) and control systems (cs.SY).
